attachments.title: Reshma Saujani: Teach girls bravery, not perfection
attachments.text: We're raising our girls to be perfect, and we're raising our boys to be brave, says Reshma Saujani, the founder of Girls Who Code. Saujani has taken up the charge to socialize young girls to take risks and learn to program -- two skills they need to move society forward. To truly innovate, we cannot leave behind half of our population, she says. "I need each of you to tell every young woman you know to be comfortable with imperfection."

attachments.title: Diversity in Tech Career Day!
attachments.text: Everyone is welcome to attend this event without regard to race, color, religion, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, national origin, disability or veteran status. The event is simply structured around celebrating and supporting gender diversity in the tech realm. This event kicks off the launch of Flock, supporting women in tech in achieving their career dreams, with a give-first event for the community! Please join Girl Develop It, Women Who Code, local Meetup groups, students, and other tech-industry community members to meet with companies looking to fill software and engineering positions. We want to prioritize human-to-human interaction over paperwork -- You'll sit down at a table and talk with team members from real companies in the Denver/Boulder area. We'll get to know each other as humans rather than just a resume. This event is all the benefits of a job fair without the pointy elbows. If you're not currently looking for a job or just want to come support the community, you're still welcome! We'll have food and plenty of open space to roam around and have great conversations.WHAT SHOULD I BRING? Bring yourself and a positive attitude! You can bring your resume, but it's not necessary. You should also come hungry - because there's free food!FOOD AND DRINK Food will be provided and beverages will be purchasable at the Galvanize bar.WHAT COMPANIES ARE COMING? The list of currently attending companies is here! This will be updated periodically as we get closer to the event!YOU'RE CHARGING MONEY? Not for job seekers and community members -- that's free!We are charging companies who want to sponsor a table and talk to our magnificent attendees. 100% of the money will be donated to fund scholarships for Girl Develop It courses, Women Who Code and the Denver Scholarship Foundation.HOSTED BY: This event is hosted by a number of organizations who share a passion for diversity: ​Flock: A career accelerator for technical humans.Flock changes the reality of minorities and women in tech. We'll supplement our client's teams with talented full-time gender-diverse contractors, but also provide them with extensive ongoing support. Each member of the 'flock' will not only accelerate their tech skills, but also become a self-confident leader for others. The companies we work with build stronger products through greater diversity of perspective.Girl Develop It: Providing affordable programs for adult women interested in learning web and software development in a judgment-free environment.Girl Develop It is a nonprofit organization that exists to provide affordable and judgment-free opportunities for women interested in learning web and software development. Through in-person classes and community support, Girl Develop It helps women of diverse backgrounds achieve their technology goals and build confidence in their careers and their every day lives.Denver Scholarship Foundation: Making college possible for thousands of students in our community. For many students in Denver, continuing their education beyond high school doesn't seem like a viable option. Most often, it's not low grades or lack of extracurricular activities keeping them from pursuing their dreams. There are thousands of intelligent, hard-working individuals facing the most intimidating barrier to college of all -- they think it just isn't possible. But the Denver Scholarship Foundation is changing that. We're making a postsecondary degree possible for Denver's students. Our unique, three-part program for college success has been nationally recognized for its effectiveness. Women Who Code: We support all women in their coding aspirations. Women Who code is a professional community for women in tech. We provide an avenue for women to pursue a career in technology, help them gain new skills and hone existing skills for professional advancement, and foster environments where networking and mentorship are valued. Whether you're a full-time programmer looking to expand your network and skills, or you have always wanted to give coding a try, you are welcome!Dialog Lab: We start conversations that fuel your business.Whether 140 pages or 140 characters, a story well told leaves a lasting impression. From traditional media relations to interactive strategies, we know how to deliver your story. Our experienced team members specialize in every facet of the communications industry. We've embraced the changing media landscape and excel at helping companies like yours fuel the hype. Galvanize: Where learning goes to work. We believe in making education and growth accessible to anyone – especially underrepresented groups in the tech industry. Whether you’re a founder, student, or just someone who wants to level up their career, we want Galvanize to be a welcoming, inclusive place where you can take the next step in your journey.Boulder JavaScript Meetup: A group focused specifically on the language that you and I both love, JavaScript. We're a friendly group and we welcome developers of all skill levels, beginner to expert. We want to foster an environment where it's okay to ask questions and it's okay not to know about certain aspects of the language. We're willing to share what we know, and are open to learning from others.Women Who Startup: Changing the face of entrepreneurship, together.Women Who Startup is dedicated to building a platform for women who are innovators, technologists, entrepreneurs, developers, educators, community members and more, with community, a powerful network and resources to fuel your current or next innovation or entrepreneurial endeavor. Join us!MergeLane: Discovering, accelerating and investing in exceptional women and the companies they run.MergeLane is broadening the onramp for women at key stages of the startup and innovation ecosystem. MergeLane accelerates high-potential female leaders and startups with at least one female in leadership. The  platform currently comprises four main pillars: The MergeLane Accelerator, Leadership Camp, MergeLane Fund, and High-Quality Content. Women Rising: A grassroots non-profit for women in tech and business to meet, connect and mentor each other. Talk to other women who are as dedicated to their careers as you are. We employ our proven algorithmic process to create "mini-meetup" groups of three that are selected by peer groups, industry, and city. If you have a specific question, you can also request a more experienced mentor to talk to. It's like online dating, but for women who influence your career. Flatirons LGBTQ Tech: LGBTQ tech meetup based in Boulder, CO. The goals for creating this meetup are: community building, service work, and professional networking/socializing for LGBTQ folks and allies in the tech/startup space in Boulder. As of September 2014, we are an official National Center for Women & Information Technology (NCWIT) Affinity Group member.All attendees are expected to abide by the Girl Develop It Code of Conduct.

messages.text:
Hello G Ladies!  Wednesday the 30th we are hosting the founder of SheEO, Vicki Saunders, at Gather from 1-3pm. 
Vicki was just featured in both Inc. Magazine and in Forbes and the event is framed around those pieces—really what is the changing landscape for funding small businesses and why does starting with a new model for funding woman-led businesses stand to make a model that benefits everyone.

Over the past 25 years, Vicki Saunders, founder of SheEO, award winning mentor, serial entrepreneur and recognized global influencer, has launched many models, companies, programs and initiatives all with the goal of finding a pathway to a better world. Recognizing that women are significantly underfunded by current models, she launched SheEO in 2015 to take advantage of women’s economic and social power to radically transform the landscape for women entrepreneurs by raising a billion dollars of capital by 2020 through individual women committing $1,000 each.

This event is open to the public, and I would love it if you could join and promote through your channels.  We hosted a SheEO event two weeks ago, it was amazing and brought some very smart, driven, and determined women into Galvanize.

<https://www.eventbrite.ca/e/the-changing-face-of-funding-with-sheeo-founder-vicki-saunders-tickets-29723816736>

attachments.title: The Changing Face of Funding with SheEO Founder Vicki Saunders
attachments.text: Join SheEO founder Vicki Saunders to discuss the changing face of funding in the entrepreneurial and start-up space.  As featured in Inc. Magazine's recent article, Female CEOs Get Only 3 Percent of Venture Funding. That's About to Change, SheEO is leading a revolution in how woman-led businesses are funded, supported, and celebrated.  SheEO isn't just out to change the funding landscape for women though, we are working to redesign a model that works poorly for all kinds of organizations that don't fit the traditional "winner-takes-all" mould today.  Join us in the Gather Lounge at Galvanize Golden Triangle to hear how a model based on Radical Generosity has the potential to revolutionize the start-up landscape and how you can get involved as an Activator, apply as a Venture, or support the movement as a HeEO!Want to know more?  Check out this recent video from Forbes: How One Entrepreneur Is Inspiring Radical Generosity in Thousands of WomenAgenda:1-1:15           Gather and Mingle1:15-1:45      Revolutionizing the Funding Landscape with SheEO (Vicki Saunders, SheEO Founder)1:45-2           Radical Generosity in Action2-2:15           SheEO in Colorado:  Why here, why now? (Jen Simpson & Heather MacKenzie, Local Leads)2:15-2:45      Q & A: How can you help catalyze this movement?2:45-3           Connection and Conversation
